<font color="#FF0000">PAT</font><br>
<tt>Sun Dec 28  8:02:22 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To deny one's self esteem, pride, and emotional and physical pain, in a self effacing manner, not to be confused with humility, is an act of self destruction.<br><br>
Too many people have an idea on how Vietnam Veterans *should* think and react. This appears as a matter of convenience for some who might not wish to face the ugly reality of it all. Most of these individuals, however, are well meaning but have no concept of the experience, the trauma, and the indelible emotional scars the Vietnam War left on its participants. This problem is compounded by the mixed messages from the population, the discrimination, abuse, derision, and hatred still manifest whenever the subject of the Vietnam War is broached. Study the historical record of posts on this site. It is all here!<br><br>
I feel the abandonment of the Vietnam Veteran by the country in general leaves little room for any criticism of his/her behavior, attitude, or point of view.<br><br>
To use religion as a wedge in these matters is even worse. Do not forget that one of the messages around at the time of the Vietnam War was that this was a war sanctfied by  mainstream religious organizations. After all, communists were atheist devils bent on the destruction of the free world and all religion. Does that cold war religious rhetoric sound familiar? It does to me.<br><br>
I am a Vietnam Veteran and very proud of it, and not the least bit ashamed of my &quot;hard core&quot; attitude. I survive because of it.     
